To be generated, the string has to be derived from one of the two start-rules

 1. S → NT130 NT45  
 2. S → NT43  NT40

------------------------
1.  S → NT130 NT45  
    NT45 can produce either  
       • the single terminal t12,  
       • the single terminal t2, or  
       • NT100 NT111, whose right-most token is produced by NT111 and must therefore be t13 or t19 (because NT111 → t13 | t19).  
    In every case the last token yielded by NT45 is t12, t2, t13 or t19.  
    The given string ends with t16, so rule 1 is impossible.

------------------------
2.  S → NT43 NT40  
    NT40’s variable rule is NT40 → NT59 NT34, otherwise it is a single terminal t3, t15, or t0.  
    Hence, if NT40 is a single terminal, the entire string would have to end with t3, t15 or t0 – it ends with t16, so that fails.  

    If NT40 → NT59 NT34, the final token of the whole string is produced by NT34 (because it is the right-most symbol).  
    NT34 can ultimately yield only  
       • the single terminals t22 or t17, or  
       • sequences ending with the terminal t6 (through its recursive alternative NT34 → NT34 NT44 with NT44 → t6), or  
       • a two-token sequence ending in t1 (via NT34 → NT101 NT12 and NT12 → t1).  
    None of these possibilities ends with t16.  
    Therefore NT40 – and thus rule 2 – cannot deliver the required final token either.

Since neither of the only two possibilities for S can produce a string whose last token is t16, the given 18-token string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

In every derivation the start symbol S expands in one step to exactly one of these two patterns  

1. S → NT130  NT45  
2. S → NT43   NT40  

Consequently the last token of any sentence generated by the grammar must be the last token produced by NT45 (for pattern 1) or by NT40 (for pattern 2).

• NT45 can only expand to  
  NT45 → 't12' | 't2' | NT100 NT111  
The two single–terminal rules end with t12 or t2.  
In the composite rule the rightmost symbol is NT111, which can only become t13 or t19.  
Hence every string derived through NT45 ends with t12, t2, t13 or t19 – never with t8.

• NT40 can only expand to  
  NT40 → 't3' | 't15' | 't0' | NT59 NT34  
The three single–terminal rules end with t3, t15 or t0.  
In NT59 NT34 the rightmost symbol is NT34, whose productions are  
  NT34 → 't22' | 't17' | NT101 NT12 | NT34 NT44  
All of these end with t22, t17, t1 or t6 (because NT12 → t1 and NT44 → t6).  
Therefore every string derived through NT40 ends with t22, t17, t1, t6, t3, t15 or t0 – never with t8.

Thus no sentence generated by the grammar can have t8 as its final token.  
The given string ends with t8, so it cannot be produced by the grammar.

The start symbol S has only two productions:

1. S → NT130 NT45  
2. S → NT43 NT40

In either case the right-most non-terminal (NT45 or NT40) must generate the final token of any derived string.

• All productions for NT45 are  
 NT45 → 't12' | 't2' | NT100 NT111  
 (The sub-non-terminals NT100, NT111 and everything they expand to ultimately generate only the terminals  
 t1, t3, t4, t6, t9, t12, t18, t19 – never t7.)

• All productions for NT40 are  
 NT40 → 't3' | 't15' | 't0' | NT59 NT34  
 (The subtree under NT59 NT34 can finally yield only the terminals  
 t1, t3, t4, t6, t18, t22, t17, t0, t15 – again, never t7.)

Thus neither NT45 nor NT40 can generate the terminal t7.  
Because the given string ends with t7, no derivation from S can yield it.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

The start symbol S has only two possible productions:

1. S → NT130 NT45  
2. S → NT43 NT40  

Hence the last token of any generated string must come from NT45 (first production) or from NT40 (second production).

1.  NT45   
    • Terminal productions: NT45 → 't12'  or  NT45 → 't2'  
    • Non-terminal production: NT45 → NT100 NT111, and  
      – NT111 → 't13'  or  NT111 → 't19'.  

   Therefore every string produced by NT45 ends with one of  
   { t12, t2, t13, t19 }.  It can never end with t1.

2.  NT40 = NT59 NT34  (or a single terminal, see below)  
    • Single-terminal alternatives: NT40 → 't3' | 't15' | 't0' (none is t1).  
    • Binary alternative: NT40 → NT59 NT34.  
      – The rightmost token of the whole NT40 yield is the rightmost token
        of NT34.  
      – NT34 can be  
          • NT34 → 't22' or 't17' (ends with t22 or t17),  
          • NT34 → NT34 NT44   (and NT44 → 't6', so the string then ends with t6),  
          • NT34 → NT101 NT12, with NT12 → 't1' and NT101 → 't3' | 't6'.  
        Thus NT34 ends with t1 only in the last case, and when that
        happens the two rightmost tokens must be either  
        t3 t1   or   t6 t1.  

   Consequently, if a string produced by S ends with t1, the
   penultimate token can only be t3 or t6.

The given string ends with the pair … t20 t1  

(both the 41st and 42nd tokens are  t20  and  t1).

Neither NT45 nor NT40 can produce a suffix t20 t1:

• NT45 can never end with t1.  
• NT40 can end with t1, but then the preceding token must be t3 or t6,
  not t20.

Therefore no derivation from S can yield the provided string.

No

To be generated, the right-most token of any sentence derived from the start symbol S must come from the right-hand non-terminal in one of the two start productions:

1. S → NT130 NT45 (the last token comes from NT45)
2. S → NT43 NT40 (the last token comes from NT40)

Hence NT45 or NT40 has to be able to yield the final token of the string, which is t20.

• NT45 can expand as  
 NT45 → NT100 NT111 | 't12' | 't2'.  
Its single-token possibilities are t12 or t2.  
In the composite form, the last token would be produced by NT111, and NT111 → 't13' | 't19'.  
Thus NT45 can end only in t12, t2, t13 or t19 – never t20.

• NT40 can expand as  
 NT40 → NT59 NT34 | 't3' | 't15' | 't0'.  
The direct terminals are t3, t15 and t0.  
If it uses NT59 NT34, the last token is produced by NT34.  
NT34 may be 't22', 't17', or (via NT34 NT44) ultimately ends in NT44, and NT44 → 't6'.  
So NT34 – and therefore NT40 – can only finish with t22, t17 or t6.

Neither NT45 nor NT40 can ever yield a terminal t20 as their last (or only) token. Consequently, no derivation from S can produce a string whose final symbol is t20.

The given string ends with t20, so it cannot be generated by this grammar.

The start symbol S has only two possible productions:

1. S → NT130 NT45  
2. S → NT43 NT40  

For any derivation, the last terminal of the generated string must come from the right-hand non-terminal of whichever alternative is chosen.

A)  If S → NT130 NT45 is used, the final token must come from NT45.  
 NT45 can produce
  • “t12”      ( NT45 → 't12' )  
  • “t2”       ( NT45 → 't2' )  
  • a string ending with “t13” or “t19” ( NT45 → NT100 NT111, where NT111 → 't13'∣'t19' ).  
 In every case the last possible token is in {t12, t2, t13, t19}.  
 It can never be “t3”.

 The given string ends with the token “t3”, so this production of S cannot match it.

B)  If S → NT43 NT40 is used, the last token must come from NT40.  
 NT40 can produce  
  • “t3”       ( NT40 → 't3' )  
  • “t15”      ( NT40 → 't15' )  
  • “t0”       ( NT40 → 't0' )  
  • a string produced by NT59 NT34 ( NT40 → NT59 NT34 ), whose last token comes from NT34.  
 NT34 can end only with “t1”, “t6”, “t7”, “t17” or “t22” (its sole terminal possibilities).  
 Therefore the only way for NT40 to end with “t3” is via the single-token rule NT40 → 't3'.

 Hence, if this alternative is chosen, NT40 contributes exactly one token (“t3”).  
 The second-to-last token of the entire string must then be the last token produced by NT43.

 NT43 → NT21 NT35, so the very last token generated by NT43 is the last token produced by NT35.  
 NT35 can end with  
  • “t3”  ( NT35 → 't3' or NT35 → NT134 NT2 with NT2 → 't3' )  
  • “t22”  ( NT35 → 't22' )  
  • “t14”  ( NT35 → NT57 NT72 with NT72 → 't14' )

 Thus NT35 can finish with only t3, t22 or t14 — never with “t9”.

 In the given string the last two tokens are “… t9 t3”.  
 Because NT35 cannot end with “t9”, the derivation S → NT43 NT40 is impossible as well.

Since neither of the only two possible top-level derivations can yield a string whose last tokens are “… t9 t3”, the provided string is not in the language of the grammar.

The start symbol S has only two productions:

1.  S → NT130 NT45   
2.  S → NT43 NT40  

The given string ends with the token t0.  
Among NT45 and NT40, only NT40 can produce the terminal t0 (NT40 → 't0').  
Therefore any derivation of the whole string must use the second production

 S ⇒ NT43 NT40,

with NT40 generating exactly the last token t0 and NT43 producing all 38 preceding tokens.

NT43 expands once:

 NT43 → NT21 NT35.

Hence the 38-token prefix has to be split into a left part generated by NT21 and a right part generated by NT35.  
The last token of that 38-token prefix is t21.

• NT35 can derive only  
 – t22 (NT35 → 't22'),  
 – t3   (NT35 → 't3'), or  
 – two-token sequences of the forms t6 t3, t4 t3, t2 t14 (via its binary productions).  
None of these possibilities contains the terminal t21, so NT35 cannot cover the suffix … t21.

Therefore the token t21 would have to be produced by NT21.  
But NT21 can yield only

 t16, t1, t19, t7

or strings containing those tokens through its binary rules (NT21 → NT50 NT5, NT14 NT51, NT27 NT100).  
None of its direct or indirect derivations can introduce the terminal t21, because t21 is produced in the grammar solely by NT77, NT33 and NT118, and none of those non-terminals occurs in any expansion path of NT21.

Consequently, there is no way to assign the token t21 to either NT35 or NT21 while respecting the structure forced by S → NT43 NT40.  
Since the alternative start-rule S → NT130 NT45 is impossible as NT45 never yields t0, the whole string cannot be derived from S.

No

For any derivation the start symbol S must use one of its two rules

1. S → NT130 NT45  
2. S → NT43 NT40

Since the string ends with the unique terminal t0, and only NT40 has the lexical rule NT40 → 't0', rule 2 must be used:

 S ⇒ NT43 NT40, NT40 ⇒ 't0'

Hence the first 41 tokens must be produced by NT43.  
NT43 has exactly one rule NT43 → NT21 NT35, so the 41-token prefix is split into

 prefix (derived from NT21) followed by suffix (derived from NT35).

NT35 can generate terminals in only three ways:

a) NT35 → 't3'  
b) NT35 → 't22'  
c) NT35 → NT134 NT2, where NT2 → 't21' and NT134 ⇒ either  
   • 't6' or • 't4' or • NT47 NT9 (with NT9 → 't12', NT47 never producing 't4' or 't12').

Thus every string derivable from NT35 must terminate in

 t3 or t22 or ( t6 t21 ) or ( t4 t21 ).

In the given string the part immediately before the final t0 is “…  t12  t21”.  
None of the possible endings listed above matches “… t12 t21”.

Therefore NT35 cannot generate the required suffix, so NT43 cannot generate the 41-token prefix, and consequently S cannot generate the whole string.

The string is not in the language of the grammar.

The start symbol has only the two productions   
S → NT130 NT45   
S → NT43 NT40  

Hence the last token in any sentence derived from S must come from the second
non-terminal on the right–hand side:

• If S → NT130 NT45, the final token is produced by NT45.  
  NT45 can only yield the single terminals t12 or t2, so a sentence derived
  via this rule must end with t12 or t2.

• If S → NT43 NT40, the final token is produced by NT40.  
  NT40 can yield only  
  – the single terminals t3, t17, t15 or t0, or  
  – a string derived from NT59 NT34.  
  NT34 ultimately ends with either t22 or t17, so any string derived through
  NT40 must end with one of {t3, t17, t15, t0, t22}.

The string to be checked ends with t19, which is not among any of the
possibilities above. Consequently it cannot be generated by either production
of S, so it is not in the language of the grammar.
